# Odin language

A data-oriented systems language: no implicit allocations, no hidden control
flow, value semantics by default. Every file opens with `package <name>`; a
package is all `.odin` files in one directory. The runtime model — the implicit
`context`, allocators, `defer`, and the `or_return` error idiom — lives in
@odin/runtime; this .jd is the grammar.

## Declarations & constants

| Form | Meaning |
|------|---------|
| `x := 10` | declare + infer type |
| `x: int = 10` | declare with explicit type |
| `x, y := 1, 2` | multiple assignment |
| `X :: 5` | compile-time constant (untyped) |
| `Y : int : 5` | typed constant |
| `x, y: int` | declare zero-initialized |

Everything is zero-initialized; there is no `null`/garbage default.

## Builtin types

- Signed `i8 i16 i32 i64 i128`, unsigned `u8 u16 u32 u64 u128`, sized `int uint uintptr`.
- Floats `f16 f32 f64`. Endian variants exist (`i32le`, `f64be`).
- `bool string rune byte any rawptr typeid`. `byte` aliases `u8`; `rune` is a 32-bit Unicode codepoint.

## Composite types

| Type | Declaration | Note |
|------|-------------|------|
| fixed array | `[5]int{1,2,3,4,5}` | length is part of the type; `[?]int{1,2,3}` infers it |
| slice | `s: []int = arr[1:4]` | a pointer+length view, no ownership |
| dynamic array | `x: [dynamic]int` then `append(&x, 9)` | grows via `context.allocator` |
| map | `m := make(map[string]int)` | `m["bob"] = 2` |
| struct | `Vector3 :: struct {x, y, z: f32}` | literal `Vector3{1,2,3}` |
| union (tagged) | `Value :: union {bool, i32, string}` | discriminated at runtime |
| enum | `Direction :: enum {North, East, South, West}` | members are `Ada_Case` |
| bit_set | `bit_set[Direction]` | `{.North, .West}` is a literal set |

## Procedures

```odin
multiply :: proc(x, y: int) -> int { return x * y }
swap     :: proc(x, y: int) -> (int, int) { return y, x }   // multiple returns
split    :: proc(in: int) -> (a, b: int) { a = in/2; b = in-a; return }  // named, bare return
greet    :: proc(name: string, loud := false) {}            // default args
sum      :: proc(nums: ..int) -> int {}                     // variadic
clone    :: proc($T: typeid, x: T) -> T {}                  // parametric polymorphism via $
```

`$T` (and `$N` for constant values) makes a proc generic; `$T/Constraint`
specializes. `loc := #caller_location` captures the call site
(`runtime.Source_Code_Location`).

## Control flow

- `if x := f(); x < 0 { } else { }` — optional init statement.
- Three `for` forms: C-style `for i := 0; i < 10; i += 1 {}`, while-form `for cond {}`, bare `for {}` (infinite), and range `for v, i in arr {}` / `for x in 0..<10 {}`. `#reverse for` walks backward.
- `switch` does **not** fall through (use `fallthrough`); group cases `case .a, .b:`. Type switch: `switch v in x { case string: ; case int: }`.
- `when COND {}` is the compile-time branch — dead arms are eliminated, no `context` needed.

## Pointers

`^T` is the pointer type, `&v` takes an address, `p^` dereferences. Selector
access auto-dereferences: `p.x = 4` needs no explicit `p^.x`.

## Packages & imports

`import "core:fmt"` then `fmt.println(...)`; alias with `import os2 "core:os"`.
Collections: `base:` `core:` `vendor:` ship with Odin; user collections are
added with `-collection:name=path` (see @odin/build) and imported `name:sub`.
Visibility: `@(private)` is package-local, `@(private="file")` is file-local.

## Naming convention (official)

Procedures and variables `snake_case`; types `Ada_Case`/`Pascal_Case`;
compile-time config constants `SCREAMING_SNAKE`.
